Case Study notebook: How Does a Bike-Share Navigate Speedy Success?

by F.I.G.L.

12 October 2022

The following steps were taken to prepare and process the data (made available by Coursera and licensed by Bikeshare):

Loaded required libraries

Read 12 data files: month <- read_csv(month.csv)

Combined all files in Year.csv: bind_rows(dec,jan, feb,mar, apr, may, jun, jul, aug, sep, oct, nov)

Combined data frame year containing 5,545,798 rows and 15 columns

Cleaned by removing 55,705 rows with missing data: year <- Year[!(Year $ trip_length == 0),]

Manipulated by reordering DoW: year $ DoW <- ordered(year $ DoW, levels=c(Sun, Mon, Tue, Wed, Thu, Fri, Sat))

tibble(year)

Performed statistical analysis on the new data frame as follows

aggregate(year$trip_length ~ year$member_casual + year$DoW, FUN = mean)
aggregate(year$trip_length ~ year$member_casual + year$DoW, FUN = min)
aggregate(year$trip_length ~ year$member_casual + year$DoW, FUN = max)

The following 3 visualizations provided additional insights that resulted in the 3 recommendations (required the scales() function).

Viz towards Recommendation #1:

Average Trip length per day of week by rider type

library(dbplyr)
library(scales)
year %>% 
    group_by(member_casual, DoW) %>%  
     summarise(totrides = n() , avg_triplength = mean(trip_length)) %>%     
     arrange(member_casual, DoW) %>%
     ggplot(aes(x = DoW, y = avg_triplength, fill = member_casual)) +
     geom_col(position = "dodge",)  +
     xlab("Day of Week") + ylab("Average Trip Length")
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'member_casual'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Viz towards Recommendation #2:

Total bike types ridden by rider type by day of week

ggplot(data=year, aes(y=member_casual, fill=rideable_type)) + geom_bar(color="white") + xlab("Total Ridden") + ylab("Rider Type") + theme_classic() +  scale_x_continuous(labels=comma)

Viz towards Recommendation #3:

Total rides per day of week per rider type
